Content: MBNMS/PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: La Cruz Rock, California, USA (LAC001)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at La Cruz Rock, California, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using a StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2007-10-20. The instrument depth was 023 meters, in an overall water depth of 23 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA (BBYX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2006-05-13. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at three locations within each site near MLLW. Temperature is recorded at 1 hour intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA (BBYX00)

Boiler Bay: BBYX00: The Boiler Bay site is located approximately 1.5 miles north of Depoe Bay on HWY 101, just north of the Boiler Bay State Scenic Viewpoint. This site is approximately 200 yards west of the parking area and contains 3 site temperature loggers in the low zone running from west to east. Site logger #1 is the western most temperature logger and is located at latitude 44.83149, longitude -124.06056, at a tidal height of 2.5 feet above Mean Lower Low Water.-124.06056-124.0605644.8314944.83149

This metadata record describes bottom-mounted ADCP data collected at Sand Hill Bluff, California, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using an RDI 600 kHz Workhorse Sentinel ADCP beginning 2001-10-26. The instrument depth was 020 meters, in an overall water depth of 021 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The instrument was programmed with a sampling interval of 2.0 minutes and a vertical resolution of 1 meter.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Cape Arago, Oregon, USA (CARX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Arago, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2010-06-17. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 5.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Middle Anacapa Island, California, USA (WIN)

Winfield Scott: WIN: The nearshore mooring is located on the North side of Middle Anacapa Island, California, USA, approximately 1 km East of Frenchys (aka Freedom Guy) Cove. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-119.395700-119.39570034.00959034.009590-003-003meter

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA (SHLX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2013-12-19. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Pelican Bay: PEL: The nearshore mooring is located on the North side of Santa Cruz Island, California, USA, approximately 0.5 km East of Pelican Bay. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA (CBLX00)

Cape Blanco, Oregon: CBLX00: The Cape Blanco site is located 6 miles north of the town of Port Orford at Cape Blanco State Park, 6 miles west of HWY 101. Altitude is height above Mean Lower Low Water (MLLW). This is a mussel growth temperature logger in the low zone of the mussel bed. -124.56567 -124.56567 42.83992 42.83992 1.12776 1.12776 meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA (BBYX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2010-08-09. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 10.0 minute intervals.

OCNMS: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Cape Elizabeth, Washington, USA (CE100)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Cape Elizabeth, Washington, USA, by OCNMS. Measurements were collected using a StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2006-05-30. The instrument depth was 010 meters, in an overall water depth of 100 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

Cape Elizabeth 100 Meter: CE100: This mooring is located on the continental shelf west of Cape Elizabeth, Washington, USA. The mooring is in approximately 100 meters of water and extends up to the sea surface. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-124.676102-124.67610247.35630147.356301-010-010meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Port Orford Head, Oregon, USA (POHX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Port Orford Head, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2010-12-07. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 10.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA (CBLS00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using HOBO Temperature/Light Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UA-002-64) beginning 2013-07-24. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 15.0 minute intervals.

The height of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in meters above the sea bottom.
The depth of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in positive meters below Mean Sea Level (MSL). Bins above MSL are represented with negative depths.

The fluctuating water depth (sea floor to sea surface distance) at the measurement site, in meters, as determined by location of sea surface from ADCP pressure measurements, or if pressure is unavailable, the maximum in ADCP echo intensity.
pressure measured at the ADCP sensor, measured in decibars with a precision defined as the effective resolution of the instrument.
ADCP echo intensity (or backscatter), in RDI counts. This value represents the average of all 4 beams, rounded to the nearest whole number.

A post-processing quantitative data quality indicator. Specifically, RDI percent-good #4, in earth coordinates (percentage of successful 4-beam transformations), expressed as a percentage, 50, 80, 95, etc.
True eastward velocity measurements. Negative values represent westward velocities.
True northward velocity measurements. Negative values represent southward velocities.
True upwards velocity measurements. Negative values represent downward velocities.
The difference of two vertical velocities, each measured by an opposing pair of ADCP beams
data flag used to qualify data as bad, questionable, etc.

Profile Point: PROXXX: The nearshore mooring is located near the West End of Santa Cruz Island, California, USA, approximately 2 km East of Profile Point. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the ADCP measurement range and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth. This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using HOBO Temperature/Light Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UA-002-64) beginning 2014-04-15. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 15.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: East Anacapa Island, California, USA (LND)

Landing Cove: LND: The nearshore mooring is located on the North side of East Anacapa Island, California, USA, adjacent to Landing Cove. The base of the mooring is in 13 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. This mooring was terminated on 27 June 2004. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-119.360700-119.36070034.01817034.018170-008-008meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Fogarty Creek, Oregon, USA (FCKX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Fogarty Creek, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2003-08-26. Mussel Growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at the mussel growth sites. Mussel growth tidbits are set to sample at 2 minute intervals from April to September and 10 minute intervals from September to April.

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Fogarty Creek, Oregon, USA (FCKX00)

Fogarty Creek: FCKX00: The Fogarty Creek site is located approximately 2 miles north of Depoe Bay at address 2425 HWY 101, just south of Fogarty Creek State Park. This site is approximately 200 yard north west of the parking area and contains 1 mussel growth temperature logger in the mid zone of the mussel bed. The logger is located at latitude 44.83870, longitude -124.05919, at a tidal height of 2.9 feet above Mean Lower Low Water.-124.05919-124.0591944.8378044.83780

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Santa Rosa Island, California, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway Tidbit Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBIC32+4+27) beginning 2005-07-27. The instrument depth was 003 meters, in an overall water depth of 015 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

Photo Plot Methods - OverviewPhoto Plot sampling is conducted by recording the number of organisms found within a permanent plot at a given site. Rectangular photo plots are photographed in the field, with plots either scored in the field, or in the lab. In general, 5 replicate plots are placed in a stratified random manner throughout the target species' zone of maximum abundance. Algae and invertebrate species counts are recorded. Please note that these data do not reflect all species present in a given area. In addition, the information in this Data Set is limited by the methods described in our survey protocols. Any site specific exceptions to the plot size and number of replicates can be found on the photo plot info table. For more information, see http://www.marine.gov/Research/Protocols.html.Photo Plot Methods - Field ScoringPhoto plots are scored in the field by using a 50 cm X 75 cm frame with a 10 X 10 grid of evenly-spaced string lines. A species, higher taxon, or substrate located below each of the 100 intersection points is identified and recorded. Layering is not scored separately, so the total cover is 100 percent.Photo Plot Methods - Lab ScoringPhoto plots are scored in the lab either from film or digital photographs. For film photographs, each slide is projected onto a white board that is marked with a grid of one hundred evenly-spaced points (10 x 10). A species, higher taxon, or substrate located below each of the 100 intersection points is identified and recorded. When scoring digital images, a grid of one hundred evenly-spaced points (10 x 10) is created on the computer monitor (using Adobe Photoshop), and placed on a separate layer. This allows the scorer to easily remove the dot to see what lies beneath. The image can then be saved with the grid layer, clearly documenting the exact points scored. With either film or digital image scoring, grid size is manipulated to provide complete coverage of the plot within the quadrapod frame. Layering is not scored separately, so the total cover is 100 percent.

Photo Plot Methods - OverviewPhoto Plot sampling is conducted by recording the number of organisms found within a permanent plot at a given site. Rectangular photo plots are photographed in the field, with plots either scored in the field, or in the lab. In general, 5 replicate plots are placed in a stratified random manner throughout the target species' zone of maximum abundance. Algae and invertebrate species counts are recorded. Please note that these data do not reflect all species present in a given area. In addition, the information in this Data Set is limited by the methods described in our survey protocols. Any site specific exceptions to the plot size and number of replicates can be found on the photo plot info table. For more information, see http://www.marine.gov/Research/Protocols.html.Photo Plot Methods - Field ScoringPhoto plots are scored in the field by using a 50 cm X 75 cm frame with a 10 X 10 grid of evenly-spaced string lines. A species, higher taxon, or substrate located below each of the 100 intersection points is identified and recorded. Layering is not scored separately, so the total cover is 100 percent.Photo Plot Methods - Lab ScoringPhoto plots are scored in the lab either from film or digital photographs. For film photographs, each slide is projected onto a white board that is marked with a grid of one hundred evenly-spaced points (10 x 10). A species, higher taxon, or substrate located below each of the 100 intersection points is identified and recorded. When scoring digital images, a grid of one hundred evenly-spaced points (10 x 10) is created on the computer monitor (using Adobe Photoshop), and placed on a separate layer. This allows the scorer to easily remove the dot to see what lies beneath. The image can then be saved with the grid layer, clearly documenting the exact points scored. With either film or digital image scoring, grid size is manipulated to provide complete coverage of the plot within the quadrapod frame. Layering is not scored separately, so the total cover is 100 percent.

OCNMS: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Cape Elizabeth, Washington, USA (CE042)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Cape Elizabeth, Washington, USA, by OCNMS. Measurements were collected using a StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2005-08-01. The instrument depth was 041 meters, in an overall water depth of 42 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Gull Haven, Oregon, USA (GHVX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Gull Haven, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2007-11-24. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 30.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Depoe Bay North, Oregon, USA (DBN40)

Depoe Bay North 40m: DBN40: The nearshore mooring is located 2.5 km offshore of Depoe Bay Harbor entrance in Depoe Bay, Oregon, USA. The base of the mooring is in 40 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-124.097437-124.09743744.81630044.816300-014-014meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Rocky Point, Oregon, USA (RKPX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Rocky Point, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using HOBO Temperature/Light Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UA-002-64) beginning 2012-08-04. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 2.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Rocky Point, Oregon, USA (RKPX00)

Rocky Point, Oregon: RKPX00: The Rocky Point site is located 3 miles south of the town of Port Orford Oregon. The site is about 0.5 miles north of the parking area. Altitude is height above Mean Lower Low Water (MLLW). This is a mussel growth temperature logger in the mid zone of the mussel bed. meter

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Gull Haven, Oregon, USA (GHVX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Gull Haven, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2007-07-13. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at three locations within each site near MLLW. Temperature is recorded at 1 hour intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Gull Haven, Oregon, USA (GHVX00)

Gull Haven: GHVX00: The Gull Haven Site is actually called Tokatee Klootchman State Wayside; it is located 8 miles south of Yachats Oregon and 17 miles north of Florence Oregon. The site is about 150 yards south of the parking area. This site contains three site loggers in the low zone and run from north to south. Site tidbit logger number three has the coordinates of latitude 44.2041, longitude -124.11649; at a tidal height of 3.6 feet above Mean Lower Low Water.-124.11649-124.1164944.204144.2041

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Santa Cruz Island, California, USA (MORXXX)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Santa Cruz Island, California, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using a StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBIC32+4+27) beginning 2010-03-24. The instrument depth was 009 meters, in an overall water depth of 15 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 4.0 minutes.

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA (CBLX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2012-04-10. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 2.0 minute intervals.

An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: bottom-mounted ADCP data: Point Sal, California, USA (PTS)

This metadata record describes bottom-mounted ADCP data collected at Point Sal, California, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using an RDI 600 kHz Workhorse Sentinel ADCP beginning 2007-03-05. The instrument depth was 015 meters, in an overall water depth of 015 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The instrument was programmed with a sampling interval of 2.0 minutes and a vertical resolution of 1 meter.

Greenwich Mean Time of each ADCP measurement record, to the 1/100th of a second, using ISO 8601 standard format hh:mm:ss.ssZ. The 'Z' indicates 'Zero Meridian' (or Greenwich Mean Time) and must be included.

Greenwich Mean Time of each ADCP measurement record, expressed as fractional decimal days since Jan. 1 of the year measurement was made. For example, 12 noon GMT on Jan. 2 is represented by yearday 1.5, NOT yearday 2.5.
The height of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in meters above the sea bottom.
The depth of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in positive meters below Mean Sea Level (MSL). Bins above MSL are represented with negative depths.

The fluctuating water depth (sea floor to sea surface distance) at the measurement site, in meters, as determined by location of sea surface from ADCP pressure measurements, or if pressure is unavailable, the maximum in ADCP echo intensity.
pressure measured at the ADCP sensor, measured in decibars with a precision defined as the effective resolution of the instrument.
ADCP echo intensity (or backscatter), in RDI counts. This value represents the average of all 4 beams, rounded to the nearest whole number.

A post-processing quantitative data quality indicator. Specifically, RDI percent-good #4, in earth coordinates (percentage of successful 4-beam transformations), expressed as a percentage, 50, 80, 95, etc.
True eastward velocity measurements. Negative values represent westward velocities.
True northward velocity measurements. Negative values represent southward velocities.
True upwards velocity measurements. Negative values represent downward velocities.
The difference of two vertical velocities, each measured by an opposing pair of ADCP beams
data flag used to qualify data as bad, questionable, etc.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: bottom-mounted ADCP data: Point Sal, California, USA (PTS)

Point Sal: PTS: The nearshore mooring is located approximately 5 km Southeast of Point Sal, California, USA. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the ADCP measurement range and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth. Note the nominal range of the ADCP may extend from near-bottom (a depth expressed as a negative altitude) to slightly above MSL (a height expressed as a positive altitude).-120.635830-120.63583034.86919034.869190-0154meter

Measurements were collected using a StowAway XTI Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. XTI32-05+37) beginning 2008-02-08. PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Fogarty Creek, Oregon, USA (FCKX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Fogarty Creek, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2001-09-17. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at three locations within each site near MLLW. Temperature is recorded at 1 hour intervals.

Fogarty Creek: FCKX00: The Fogarty Creek site is located approximately 2 miles north of Depoe Bay at address 2425 HWY 101, just south of Fogarty Creek State Park. CINMS/PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Santa Rosa Island, California, USA (BEAXXX)

Beacon Rock: BEAXXX: The nearshore mooring is located off Carrington Point on the Northeast end of Santa Rosa Island, California, USA, approximately 1.7 km ESE of Beacon Rock. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-120.031370-120.03137034.03849034.038490-014-014meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

Measurements were collected using an RDI 600 kHz Workhorse Sentinel ADCP beginning 2003-08-01. PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Seal Rock, Oregon, USA (SRKX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Seal Rock, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2007-09-28. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 30.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Manipulation Bay, Oregon, USA (MBYX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Manipulation Bay, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using HOBO Temperature/Light Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UA-002-64) beginning 2012-01-12. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 15.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Manipulation Bay, Oregon, USA (MBYX00)

Manipulation Bay, Oregon is located directly north of the Bioler Bay/Government Point State Park parking lot. This is at the north end of the town of Depoe Bay, Oregon. The site is a part of the Cape Foulweather site complex that includes Bioler Bay, Fogarty Creek and Manipulation Bay (historically some sites that are refered to as Depoe Bay, Boiler Bay South, and Boiler Bay North. Altitude is height above Mean Lower Low Water (MLLW). This is a site temperature logger in the intertidal low zone. -124.06255 -124.06255 44.83005 44.83005 0.00000 0.00000 meter

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Santa Cruz Island, California, USA (HAZ)

Hazard Anchorage: HAZ: The nearshore mooring is located on the North side of Santa Cruz Island, California, USA, approximately 0.3 km Southeast of Hazard Anchorage. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. This mooring was terminated on 7 January 2005. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-119.823640-119.82364034.05929034.059290-014-014meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Seal Rock 15m, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using a HOBO U12 Themocouple Logger (Onset Computer Corp. U12-014) beginning 2006-07-18. The instrument depth was 001 meters, in an overall water depth of 15 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

Seal Rock 15m: SR15XX: The nearshore mooring is located directly offshore of the onshore Seal Rock site, in the town of Seal Rock, Oregon, USA. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. MLPA baseline: Subtidal: Community Surveys: Fish Surveys

This metadata record documents the size frequency surveys for PISCO subtidal community surveys. Size frequency sampling consists of recording the number and size of target invertebrate species (urchins of the genus Strongylocentrotus and abalone of the genus Haliotis). Indivduals are encountered and recorded either as part of normal swath surveys, or during random swims anywhere within the survey site. Subtidal community structure surveys are conducted annually at all sites during the summer or early fall, and quantify substrate type and relief, benthic cover, abundance of major groups of macroalgae and invertebrates, and abundance and size of fishes. Spatial allocation of sampling is designed to measure year-to-year site-wide variability in community structure and the spatial scales at which such variation occurs. A site is defined as a fixed stretch of coastline, occupying approximately 500m. Originally, each site was divided into 2 halves (sides), each comprised of 12 transects startified across the four zones described above. Starting in 2007, many new sites were added for monitoring MPAs established by the MLPA along the coast of central California. These MLPA sites are equivalent of one 'side' of the orignal PISCO sites (i.e. 12 transects).

Shell diameters (abalone) or diameter of test and spines (urchins) are measured by divers in situ. In the case of urchins sampled by UCSB in the channel islands, large numbers of individuals may be collected in bags and brought aboard the research vessel to facilitate measurement. PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA (SHLX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2006-10-09. Mussel Growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at the mussel growth sites. Mussel growth tidbits are set to sample at 2 minute intervals from April to September and 10 minute intervals from September to April.

Strawberry Hill: SHLX00: The Strawberry Hill site is located 5 miles south of Yachats, Oregon and 20 miles North of Florence Oregon. It is located in the Cape Perpetua Scenic Area. The site is about 300 yards south of the parking area. This site contains three mussel growth loggers that are located in the high, mid, and low zones of the mussel bed. Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA (CBLX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2012-07-06. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 5.0 minute intervals.

Cape Blanco, Oregon: CBLX00: The Cape Blanco site is located 6 miles north of the town of Port Orford at Cape Blanco State Park, 6 miles west of HWY 101. Altitude is height above Mean Lower Low Water (MLLW). This is a site temperature logger in the intertidal low zone. -124.56568 -124.56568 42.83969 42.83969 0.88392 0.88392 meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

CINMS/PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Santa Rosa Island, California, USA (SRSXXX)

Santa Rosa South: SRSXXX: The nearshore mooring is located on the South side of Santa Rosa Island, California, USA, approximately 1 km Northwest of South Point. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-120.128420-120.12842033.89511033.895110-014-014meter

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Rocky Point, Oregon, USA (RKPX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Rocky Point, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2005-11-17. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at three locations within each site near MLLW. Temperature is recorded at 1 hour intervals.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Lincoln Beach 15m, Oregon, USA (LB15XX)

Lincoln Beach 15m: LB15XX: The nearshore mooring is located offshore of Lincoln Beach, approximately 2km North of the onshore Fogarty Creek site, about 5km North of Depoe Bay, Oregon, USA. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth. -124.0591667 -124.0591667 44.85996667 44.85996667 -001 -001 meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Strawberry Hill North 15m, Oregon, USA (SHN15X)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Strawberry Hill North 15m, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using a Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2012-04-21. The instrument depth was 014 meters, in an overall water depth of 15 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Sand Hill Bluff, California, USA (SHB001)

Sand Hill Bluff: SHB001: This inner-shelf mooring is located on the northwestern edge of Monterey Bay, California, USA, approximately 10 km West of the city of Santa Cruz. The mooring lies in an overall water depth of 021 meters (referenced to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-122.158450-122.15845036.97212136.972121-005-005meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Fogarty Creek, Oregon, USA (FCKX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Fogarty Creek, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2008-06-20. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 5.0 minute intervals.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA (CBLX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2010-05-20. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 5.0 minute intervals.

Measurements were collected using StowAway XTI Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. XTI32-05+37) beginning 2003-01-30. The instrument depth was 017 meters, in an overall water depth of 018 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Yachats Beach, Oregon, USA (YBHX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Yachats Beach, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2011-07-15. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 5.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: bionic mussel temperature data: Rocky Point, Oregon, USA (RKPX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Rocky Point, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using micro-T Temperature Logger (NexSens DS1921G) beginning 2010-05-20. Bionic mussel temperature loggers are contained within an artificial mussel in the middle of the mussel bed. There are typically two replicates with two loggers within each replicate. These are distinguished in the file name as follows: R11 - replicate 1, 1st logger; R12 - replicate 1, 2nd logger; R21 - replicate 2, 1st logger; R22 - replicate 2, 2nd logger. Temperature is recorded at 60.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: bionic mussel temperature data: Cape Arago, Oregon, USA (CARX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Arago, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using micro-T Temperature Logger (NexSens DS1921G) beginning 2004-04-24. Bionic mussel temperature loggers are contained within an artificial mussel in the middle of the mussel bed. There are typically two replicates with two loggers within each replicate. These are distinguished in the file name as follows: R11 - replicate 1, 1st logger; R12 - replicate 1, 2nd logger; R21 - replicate 2, 1st logger; R22 - replicate 2, 2nd logger. Temperature is recorded at 60.0 minute intervals.

Greenwich Mean Time calendar date of each ADCP measurement record, using ISO 8601 standard format YYYY-MM-DD

Greenwich Mean Time of each ADCP measurement record, to the 1/100th of a second, using ISO 8601 standard format hh:mm:ss.ssZ. The 'Z' indicates 'Zero Meridian' (or Greenwich Mean Time) and must be included.

Greenwich Mean Time of each ADCP measurement record, expressed as fractional decimal days since Jan. 1 of the year measurement was made. For example, 12 noon GMT on Jan. 2 is represented by yearday 1.5, NOT yearday 2.5.
The height of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in meters above the sea bottom.
The depth of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in positive meters below Mean Sea Level (MSL). Bins above MSL are represented with negative depths.

The fluctuating water depth (sea floor to sea surface distance) at the measurement site, in meters, as determined by location of sea surface from ADCP pressure measurements, or if pressure is unavailable, the maximum in ADCP echo intensity.
pressure measured at the ADCP sensor, measured in decibars with a precision defined as the effective resolution of the instrument.
ADCP echo intensity (or backscatter), in RDI counts. This value represents the average of all 4 beams, rounded to the nearest whole number.

A post-processing quantitative data quality indicator. Specifically, RDI percent-good #4, in earth coordinates (percentage of successful 4-beam transformations), expressed as a percentage, 50, 80, 95, etc.
True eastward velocity measurements. Negative values represent westward velocities.
True northward velocity measurements. Negative values represent southward velocities.
True upwards velocity measurements. Negative values represent downward velocities.
The difference of two vertical velocities, each measured by an opposing pair of ADCP beams
data flag used to qualify data as bad, questionable, etc.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: bottom-mounted ADCP data: Stillwater Cove, California, USA (SWC001)

Stillwater Cove: SWC001: This inner-shelf mooring is located at the mouth of Stillwatrer Cove, in Carmel Bay, California, USA. The mooring is located in an overall water depth of 022 meters (referenced to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the ADCP measurement range and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth. Note the nominal range of the ADCP may extend from near-bottom (a depth expressed as a negative altitude) to slightly above MSL (a height expressed as a positive altitude).-121.944800-121.94480036.55800036.558000-021-2meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Seal Rock, Oregon, USA (SR15)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Seal Rock, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using HOBO U12 Thermocouple Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. U12-014) beginning 2005-04-26. The instrument depth was 001 meters, in an overall water depth of 15 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

Seal Rock 15m: SR15: The nearshore mooring is located directly offshore of the onshore Seal Rock site, in the town of Seal Rock, Oregon, USA. PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Cape Arago, Oregon, USA (CARX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Arago, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2014-04-30. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 5.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: bionic mussel temperature data: Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA (CBLX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using micro-T Temperature Logger (NexSens DS1921G) beginning 2011-06-16. Bionic mussel temperature loggers are contained within an artificial mussel in the middle of the mussel bed. There are typically two replicates with two loggers within each replicate. These are distinguished in the file name as follows: R11 - replicate 1, 1st logger; R12 - replicate 1, 2nd logger; R21 - replicate 2, 1st logger; R22 - replicate 2, 2nd logger. Temperature is recorded at 60.0 minute intervals.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Goleta, California, USA (ELL)

Ellwood Pier: ELL: The nearshore mooring is located just off the end of Ellwood Pier, near the western boundary of Goleta, California, USA. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-119.932030-119.93203034.42403034.424030-009-009meter

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Santa Cruz Island, California, USA (VALXXX)

Valley Anchorage: VALXXX: The nearshore mooring is located on South side of Santa Cruz Island, California, USA, adjacent to Valley Anchorage. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-119.669340-119.66934033.97762033.977620-009-009meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA (SHLX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2010-03-28. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 10.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Hopkins Marine Station, California, USA (HMS001)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Hopkins Marine Station, California, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using a StowAway XTI Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. XTI32-05+37) beginning 2010-08-09. The instrument depth was 018 meters, in an overall water depth of 20 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA (SHLX00)

Strawberry Hill: SHLX00: The Strawberry Hill site is located 5 miles south of Yachats, Oregon and 20 miles North of Florence Oregon. It is located in the Cape Perpetua Scenic Area. The site is about 300 yards south of the parking area. This site contains three site loggers that are located in the low zone and run from north to southeast. Site logger number one has the coordinates of latitude 44.24996, longitude -124.11542; at a tidal height of 2.5 feet above Mean Lower Low Water.-124.11542-124.1154244.2499644.24996

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA (SH15)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway XTI Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. XTI32-05+37) beginning 2001-06-19. The instrument depth was 004 meters, in an overall water depth of 15 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA (SH15)

Strawberry Hill 15m: SH15: The nearshore mooring is located Strawberry Hill: directly offshore of the onshore Strawberry Hill site, approximately 1 km South of the Strawberry Hill, Oregon, USA. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-124.127332-124.12733244.25230044.252300-004-004meter

Measurements were collected using StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2007-07-13. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. PISCO: Intertidal: Recruitment Monitoring: UCSB: Plate: 2005

This metadata record documents the recruitment monitoring study for PISCO intertidal. Settlement collectors are deployed and rock surfaces cleared at various sites along the pacific coast of California and Oregon. At each site there are two types of collectors. Collectors made of plastic mesh, ovoid, pot-scrubbers ('Tuffys') target mussel recruits. Plastic 10x10 cm PVC plates covered with 3M Safety-Walk target barnacle recruitment. 10x10 cm square plots were cleared on the rock near each barnacle recruitment plate to target natural barnacle recruitment. All collectors were deployed and plots cleared in the mid zone at all the sites throughout the year. Additional collectors and plots were added to the low and high shore levels in specific years and sites. Although mussels and barnacles were the main target taxa, other organisms were recorded as well.

Recruitment Monitoring MethodsCollectors are taken to the lab for processing, and rock clearings are counted directly in the field. Number of recruits is determined from direct counts of organisms extracted from mussel collectors or found on plates and clearings. When the number appears to be very high sub-samples are taken. For more information, see the full data protocols at http://www.piscoweb.org/research/recruitment.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Fogarty Creek, Oregon, USA (FCKX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Fogarty Creek, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2003-07-14. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at three locations within each site near MLLW. Temperature is recorded at 1 hour intervals.

OCNMS: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Makah Bay, Washington, USA (MB042)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Makah Bay, Washington, USA, by OCNMS. Measurements were collected using a StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2004-08-31. PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA (BBYX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway Tidbit Temperature Logger (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2006-11-06. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 60.0 minute intervals.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

The height of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in meters above the sea bottom.

True eastward velocity measurements. Negative values represent westward velocities.
True northward velocity measurements. Negative values represent southward velocities.
True upwards velocity measurements. Negative values represent downward velocities.
The difference of two vertical velocities, each measured by an opposing pair of ADCP beams

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

Anacapa South: ANSXXX: The nearshore mooring is located on the South side of East Anacapa Island, California, USA, approximately 1 km West of Arch Rock. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Cape Meares, Oregon, USA (CMRX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Meares, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2012-07-23. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 5.0 minute intervals.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

The height of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in meters above the sea bottom.
The depth of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in positive meters below Mean Sea Level (MSL). Bins above MSL are represented with negative depths.

The fluctuating water depth (sea floor to sea surface distance) at the measurement site, in meters, as determined by location of sea surface from ADCP pressure measurements, or if pressure is unavailable, the maximum in ADCP echo intensity.
pressure measured at the ADCP sensor, measured in decibars with a precision defined as the effective resolution of the instrument.
ADCP echo intensity (or backscatter), in RDI counts. This value represents the average of all 4 beams, rounded to the nearest whole number.

A post-processing quantitative data quality indicator. Specifically, RDI percent-good #4, in earth coordinates (percentage of successful 4-beam transformations), expressed as a percentage, 50, 80, 95, etc.
True eastward velocity measurements. Negative values represent westward velocities.
True northward velocity measurements. Negative values represent southward velocities.
True upwards velocity measurements. Negative values represent downward velocities.
The difference of two vertical velocities, each measured by an opposing pair of ADCP beams

Valley Anchorage: VALXXX: The nearshore mooring is located on South side of Santa Cruz Island, California, USA, adjacent to Valley Anchorage. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Cape Arago, Oregon, USA (CARX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Arago, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2011-04-21. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 5.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: bionic mussel temperature data: Yachats Beach, Oregon, USA (YBHX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Yachats Beach, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using micro-T Temperature Logger (NexSens DS1921G) beginning 2004-04-20. Bionic mussel temperature loggers are contained within an artificial mussel in the middle of the mussel bed. There are typically two replicates with two loggers within each replicate. These are distinguished in the file name as follows: R11 - replicate 1, 1st logger; R12 - replicate 1, 2nd logger; R21 - replicate 2, 1st logger; R22 - replicate 2, 2nd logger. Temperature is recorded at 60.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Soquel Point, California, USA (SQP001)

Soquel Point: SQP001: This nearshore mooring is located offshore of the city of Santa Cruz, California, USA, near Pleasure Point. The mooring lies in an overall water depth of 021 meters (referenced to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-121.975200-121.97520036.93770036.937700-012-012meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Santa Cruz Island, California, USA (SCP)

Cavern Point: SCP: The nearshore mooring is located toward the Northeast End of Santa Cruz Island, California, USA, approximately 200m Southeast of Cavern Point. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Rocky Point, Oregon, USA (RKPX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Rocky Point, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2010-04-19. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 5.0 minute intervals.

The height of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in meters above the sea bottom.
The depth of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in positive meters below Mean Sea Level (MSL). Bins above MSL are represented with negative depths.

The fluctuating water depth (sea floor to sea surface distance) at the measurement site, in meters, as determined by location of sea surface from ADCP pressure measurements, or if pressure is unavailable, the maximum in ADCP echo intensity.
pressure measured at the ADCP sensor, measured in decibars with a precision defined as the effective resolution of the instrument.
ADCP echo intensity (or backscatter), in RDI counts. This value represents the average of all 4 beams, rounded to the nearest whole number.

A post-processing quantitative data quality indicator. Specifically, RDI percent-good #4, in earth coordinates (percentage of successful 4-beam transformations), expressed as a percentage, 50, 80, 95, etc.
True eastward velocity measurements. Negative values represent westward velocities.
True northward velocity measurements. Negative values represent southward velocities.
True upwards velocity measurements. Negative values represent downward velocities.
The difference of two vertical velocities, each measured by an opposing pair of ADCP beams

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Seal Rock, Oregon, USA (SRKX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Seal Rock, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2006-05-16. Mussel Growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at the mussel growth sites. Mussel growth tidbits are set to sample at 2 minute intervals from April to September and 10 minute intervals from September to April.

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA (BBYX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Boiler Bay, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2010-12-05. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 10.0 minute intervals.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.
