PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Santa Cruz Island, California, USA (SCP)

Cavern Point: SCP: The nearshore mooring is located toward the Northeast End of Santa Cruz Island, California, USA, approximately 200m Southeast of Cavern Point. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-119.559410-119.55941034.05559034.055590-014-014meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Twelve Mile Beach, New Zealand (TMBX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Twelve Mile Beach, New Zealand by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2004-03-21. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at locations within each site in the High, Mid, and/or Low zones. Temperature is recorded at 1 hour intervals.

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO) PISCO Consortium PISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs. PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Santa Cruz Island, California, USA (TRLXXX)

Trailer: TRLXXX: The nearshore mooring is located near the West End of Santa Cruz Island, California, USA, approximately 0.7 km Southeast of Forney Cove. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-119.910510-119.91051034.05011034.050110-014-014meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Gaviota State Park, California, USA (ALE)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at Gaviota State Park, California, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway Tidbit Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBIC32+4+27) beginning 2004-12-19. The instrument depth was 014 meters, in an overall water depth of 015 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was -26.9 minutes.

PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: Depoe Bay North, Oregon, USA (DBN15)

Depoe Bay North 15m: DBN15: The nearshore mooring is located 1 km offshore of Depoe Bay Harbor entrance in Depoe Bay, Oregon, USA. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-124.075737-124.07573744.81620044.816200-009-009meter

Partnership for Interdisciplinary Studies of Coastal Oceans (PISCO)PISCOConsortiumPISCO is a large-scale marine research program that focuses on understanding the near-shore ecosystems of the U.S. West Coast. An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

PISCO: Intertidal: site temperature data: Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA (CBLX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Blanco, Oregon, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway TidbiT Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBI32-05+37) beginning 2007-07-16. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at three locations within each site near MLLW. Temperature is recorded at 1 hour intervals.

An interdisciplinary collaboration of scientists from four universities, PISCO integrates long-term monitoring of ecological and oceanographic processes at dozens of coastal sites with experimental work in the lab and field. We explore how individual organisms, populations, and ecological communities vary over space and time. Findings are applied to issues of ocean conservation and management, and are shared through our public outreach and student training programs.PISCO is funded by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

CINMS/PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: San Miguel Island, California, USA (BAYXXX)

This metadata record describes moored seawater temperature data collected at San Miguel Island, California, USA, by PISCO. Measurements were collected using StowAway Tidbit Temperature Loggers (Onset Computer Corp. TBIC32+4+27) beginning 2007-03-11. The instrument depth was 014 meters, in an overall water depth of 015 meters (both relative to Mean Sea Level, MSL). The sampling interval was 2.0 minutes.

CINMS/PISCO: Physical Oceanography: moored temperature data: San Miguel Island, California, USA (BAYXXX)

Bay Point: BAYXXX: The nearshore mooring is located on the North side of San Miguel Island, California, USA, approximately 0.7 km Southeast of Bay Point. The base of the mooring is in 15 meters of water below Mean Sea Level (MSL), and it extends up to 4 meters below MSL. The altitudeMinimum and altitudeMaximum tags in this initial coverage section refer to the logger measurement range (with depths expressed as negative altitudes) and are also referenced to MSL. They do not represent the overall water depth.-120.311210-120.31121034.04017034.040170-014-014meter

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Cape Meares, Oregon, USA (CMRX00)

This metadata record describes a mix of intertidal seawater and air temperature data collected at Cape Meares, Oregon, USA by PISCO. Measurements were collected using Onset Tidbit V2 Temp Data Logger (Onset Computer Corp. UTBI-001) beginning 2009-09-20. Site temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at various locations within each site. Mussel growth temperature loggers are bolted down in a wire cage at high, mid, or low positions within a mussel bed. Temperature is recorded at 2.0 minute intervals.

PISCO: Intertidal: mussel growth temperature data: Cape Meares, Oregon, USA (CMRX00)

Cape Meares, Oregon: CMRX00: The Cape Meares site is located approximately 10 miles west of Tillamook just south of the Cape Meares lighthouse. This site is approximately 300 yards southwest of the parking area. Altitude is height above Mean Lower Low Water (MLLW). This is a mussel growth temperature logger in the mid zone of the mussel bed. -123.97224 -123.97224 45.47173 45.47173 1.95072 1.95072 meter
